<subsection xml:id="subsec-applying-quadratic-identities-in-numerical-cases" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quadratic Identities.</title>

    <p>
        Quadratic identities can be used to simplify numerical expressions and solve equations efficiently.
    </p>

    <activity>
        <p>
            <em><term>Work Groups</term></em>
        </p>
        
        <p>
            
        </p>
        
    </activity>

    <p>
        From the previous lessons and exercises, not that;
        <md>
            <mrow> (x = 2)^2 \amp = x^2 + 4x+ 4, </mrow>
        </md>
        <md>
            <mrow>(x - 3)^2 \amp = x^2 - 6x + 9, </mrow>
        </md>
        and
        <md>
            <mrow> (x + 2a)(x - 2a) \amp = x^2 -4a^2 </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
    <p>
        In general, the quadratic identities are;
        <ol marker="i">
            <li>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>(a + b)^2 \amp = a^2 + 2ab +b^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> (a - b)^2 \amp = a^2 - 2ab + b^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> (a + b)(a - b) \amp = a^2 - b^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    (Difference of two squares)
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        The three identites are useful in expansion and factorisation of many quadratic expressions.
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the quadratic identities to write
                down the expansions of each of the
                following expressions:
                <me>
                    (x + 5)^2
                </me>                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To expand <m>(x + 5)^2</m>  using the quadratic identity, we can apply the formula for squaring a binomial:
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    (a + b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2
                </me>
                here <m>a = x</m> and <m>b = 5</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Square the first term, <m>a^2 = x^2</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Multiply the first and second terms, <m>2ab = 2(x)(5) = 10x</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Square the second term, <m>b^2 = 5^2 = 25</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Now putting all the terms together, we have;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    (x + 5)^2 = x^2 + 10x + 25
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                So, the expected expansion of <m>(x + 5)^2</m> is;
                <me>x^2 + 10x + 25</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use the quadratic identities to write
                down the expansions of each of the
                following expressions:
                <me>
                    \left( \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{y} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{y} \right)
                </me>                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To form a quadratic expression we just have to expand the expression;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    \left( \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{y} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{y} \right)
                </me>
                <me>
                    \left( \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{y} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{y} \right) = \left(\frac{1}{x} \times \frac{1}{x} \right) - \left( \frac{1}{x} \times \frac{1}{y} \right) + \left(\frac{1}{y} \times \frac{1}{x} \right) - \left(\frac{1}{y} \times \frac{1}{y} \right)
                </me>
                Simplifying the expression, we have;
                <me>
                   \left( \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{y} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{y} \right) = \frac{1}{x^2} - \frac{1}{xy} + \frac{1}{xy} - \frac{1}{y^2}
                </me>
                Cancling out the like terms we;
                <me>
                    \left( \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{y} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{y} \right)  = \frac{1}{x^2} - \frac{1}{y^2}
                </me>                
            </p>
            <p>
                So, the expected expansion of <m>\left( \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{y} \right) \left( \frac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{y} \right)</m> is;
                <me>\left( \frac{1}{x^2} - \frac{1}{y^2} \right)</me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Form a quadratic expression using the expansion method.
                <me>
                    (x + 2)(x + 3)
                </me>                
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To form a quadratic expression using the expansion method, we multiply the two binomials:
                <md>
                    <mrow> (x + 2)(x + 3) = \amp x^2 + 3x + 2x + 6  </mrow>
                </md>            
            </p>
            <p>
                Collecting like terms together we form;
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 5x + 6 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                
                Thus the expanded form of expression <m>(x + 2)(x + 3)</m> is;
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    x^2 + 5x + 6
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Form a quadratic expression using the square of a binomial.
                <me>
                    (x + 2)^2
                </me>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To form a quadratic expression using the square of a binomial, we square the binomial:
                <md>
                    <mrow> (x + 2)^2 = \amp (x + 2)(x + 2) </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Expanding the binomial we get;
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 2x + 2x + 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Collecting like terms together we form;
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp x^2 + 4x + 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Thus the expanded form of expression <m>(x + 2)^2</m> is;
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> = \amp  x^2 + 4x + 4 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
